Note: ============================================================================
Note: Dockerfile Lexer - Complete tokenization for Dockerfile syntax
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Handles all Dockerfile instructions, multi-line commands, variables, heredocs
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as CharCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Dockerfile Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Instructions
Constant TOKEN_FROM as Integer is 100
Constant TOKEN_RUN as Integer is 101
Constant TOKEN_CMD as Integer is 102
Constant TOKEN_LABEL as Integer is 103
Constant TOKEN_EXPOSE as Integer is 104
Constant TOKEN_ENV as Integer is 105
Constant TOKEN_ADD as Integer is 106
Constant TOKEN_COPY as Integer is 107
Constant TOKEN_ENTRYPOINT as Integer is 108
Constant TOKEN_VOLUME as Integer is 109
Constant TOKEN_USER as Integer is 110
Constant TOKEN_WORKDIR as Integer is 111
Constant TOKEN_ARG as Integer is 112
Constant TOKEN_ONBUILD as Integer is 113
Constant TOKEN_STOPSIGNAL as Integer is 114
Constant TOKEN_HEALTHCHECK as Integer is 115
Constant TOKEN_SHELL as Integer is 116
Constant TOKEN_MAINTAINER as Integer is 117  Note: Deprecated but still used

Note: Keywords
Constant TOKEN_AS as Integer is 200
Constant TOKEN_NONE as Integer is 201  Note: For HEALTHCHECK NONE

Note: Flags (for COPY/ADD)
Constant TOKEN_FLAG as Integer is 300  Note: --from, --chown, --chmod, etc.

Note: Literals and identifiers
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 400
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 401
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 402
Constant TOKEN_VARIABLE as Integer is 403  Note: $VAR or ${VAR}
Constant TOKEN_IMAGE_REF as Integer is 404  Note: image:tag or image@digest

Note: JSON syntax
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 500
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 501
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 502

Note: Image-reference separators (image:tag@digest)
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 503
Constant TOKEN_AT as Integer is 504

Note: Operators
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 600
Constant TOKEN_BACKSLASH as Integer is 601  Note: Line continuation

Note: Heredoc
Constant TOKEN_HEREDOC_START as Integer is 700
Constant TOKEN_HEREDOC_CONTENT as Integer is 701
Constant TOKEN_HEREDOC_END as Integer is 702

Note: Special
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 800
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 801
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 802
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 803

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile lexer is single-pass and line-oriented. It needs the
source string, a byte position cursor, line/column counters for
diagnostics, the currently-decoded character (so peek_ahead can look
beyond the cursor without re-decoding), an emitted token list, and an
error flag plus message for the first lex failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Eight fields: source (input String), position (zero-based byte offset),
line (1-based), column (1-based), current_char (codepoint at position
or 0 at EOF), tokens (handle to a ListCore List of DockerfileToken
values), had_error (0/1 sticky flag), error_message (String, "" when
no error).
@End Implementation
Type called "DockerfileLexerState":
    source as String
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    current_char as Integer        Note: Character code point
    tokens as Integer              Note: List of tokens
    had_error as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
    error_message as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Each emitted token carries the TOKEN_* kind constant, the source
substring that produced it, position info for diagnostics, and a
separate literal_value for processed forms (e.g. de-escaped string
contents or numeric values converted from text). Storing both lexeme
and literal_value lets the parser format diagnostics with the original
text while consuming the cooked literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five fields: token_type (TOKEN_* discriminant), lexeme (the raw source
slice), line and column (1-based, pointing to the lexeme's start),
literal_value (cooked value or empty when lexeme is already canonical).
@End Implementation
Type called "DockerfileToken":
    token_type as Integer
    lexeme as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    literal_value as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs a DockerfileLexerState value, allocates a heap home for it,
and primes the current_char field so the first call to scan_token does
not have to special-case the empty cursor. Returning a pointer keeps
the lexer state mutable across the public lexer entry points.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a DockerfileLexerState value with source set, position=0,
line=1, column=1, current_char=0 initial sentinel, tokens=fresh List
from ListCore, had_error=0, empty error_message. Struct construction
allocates the heap home directly. If the source is non-empty reads the
first character via StringCore.string_char_at and updates current_char
in place. Returns the struct pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_lexer" takes source as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create and initialize Dockerfile lexer state.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be a value of type DockerfileLexerState with
        source as source,
        position as 0,
        line as 1,
        column as 1,
        current_char as 0,
        tokens as proc list_create from ListCore,
        had_error as 0,
        error_message as ""

    Note: Initialize current_char
    If proc string_length from StringCore with source is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, 0
        Set lexer.current_char to first_char
    End If

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Advancing the cursor must keep three things in sync: byte position,
line/column counters (for diagnostics), and current_char (for cheap
lookup by scanners). Newline detection bumps the line counter and
resets column to 1 so post-newline positions are correct.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Operates on the lexer struct in place. Captures the current character
to return at the end. Increments position and column by 1. If the
previous character was 10 (newline) bumps line and resets column to 1.
Reads the next character via StringCore.string_char_at when
position < source length; otherwise stores 0 as the EOF sentinel.
Returns the character that was current at the start of the call.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Move to next character, update position tracking.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with lexer.source

    Let current be lexer.current_char

    Set lexer.position to lexer.position plus 1
    Set lexer.column to lexer.column plus 1

    Note: Check for newline
    If current is equal to 10:  Note: '\n'
        Set lexer.line to lexer.line plus 1
        Set lexer.column to 1
    End If

    Note: Update current_char
    If lexer.position is less than source_len:
        Let next_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with lexer.source, lexer.position
        Set lexer.current_char to next_char
    Otherwise:
        Set lexer.current_char to 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Return current
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constant-time non-consuming character access. Returns the already-
decoded current_char field, so callers do not pay for re-decoding the
character at the cursor on every check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the DockerfileLexerState struct from lexer_ptr and returns its
current_char field directly. Returns 0 at EOF (current_char carries the
EOF sentinel after advance walks past end of source).
@End Implementation
Process called "peek" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Look at current character without consuming.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Return lexer.current_char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-character lookahead is needed for two-character tokens (==, &&,
etc.) and for distinguishing line continuations from independent
backslashes. The variable offset lets callers reach arbitrary distances
without re-reading current_char first.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer struct. Computes look_pos = position + offset. If
look_pos is within source bounds, returns the character at that
position via StringCore.string_char_at. Otherwise returns 0 (EOF
sentinel). Does NOT mutate lexer state.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer_ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Look ahead at character at given offset.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Let look_pos be lexer.position plus offset
    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with lexer.source

    If look_pos is less than source_len:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with lexer.source, look_pos
        Return char
    End If

    Return 0  Note: EOF
End Process

@Reasoning:
Uses current_char==0 as the EOF sentinel rather than re-checking
position vs source length, so this is a single field read instead of a
length computation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer struct. Returns 1 if current_char is 0, otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_at_end" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if at end of source.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr

    If lexer.current_char is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile syntax is line-oriented so newline must NOT be treated as
whitespace; only space (32) and tab (9) are. This routine implements
that policy in one place so scanners do not have to remember the
exclusion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if char equals 32 (space) or 9 (tab); otherwise returns 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if character is whitespace (space or tab, NOT newline).
    @End Reasoning

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: ' '
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: '\t'
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII-only alpha check (no Unicode). Dockerfile instruction names and
identifiers are restricted to ASCII so an ICU-aware classifier would
be wasted overhead and would also accept names that the engine would
later reject.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 when char is in [65..90] (A-Z) or [97..122] (a-z). Otherwise
returns 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if character is alphabetic.
    @End Reasoning

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: A-Z
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: a-z
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII decimal digit predicate, matching the Dockerfile-allowed numeric
character set. Hex digits etc. are not handled here because Dockerfile
literals do not require them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 when char is in [48..57] (0-9), otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if character is a digit.
    @End Reasoning

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: 0-9
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile identifiers include the usual alphanumeric/underscore set
plus hyphen (image tags like `python-slim`), dot (versions like
`alpine:3.18`), and forward slash (registry paths like
`gcr.io/project/image`). This wider character set is the one downstream
parsers expect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to is_alpha and is_digit for letter/digit categories. Then
returns 1 for the explicit punctuation codepoints: 95 (_), 45 (-),
46 (.), 47 (/). Returns 0 for anything else.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_identifier_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if character can be part of identifier (alphanumeric, underscore, hyphen, dot).
    @End Reasoning

    If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Tokens have a fixed shape across all kinds, so a single factory keeps
the lexer scanners focused on classification and value extraction. The
factory always allocates on the heap because the tokens are stored in
the lexer's token list across calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a DockerfileToken value with the five supplied fields. Struct
construction allocates the heap home directly. Returns the struct
pointer; ownership transfers to whatever list ultimately holds it.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as String, line as Integer, column as Integer, literal_value as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create new token with given properties.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token be a value of type DockerfileToken with
        token_type as token_type,
        lexeme as lexeme,
        line as line,
        column as column,
        literal_value as literal_value

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combines token creation and list append behind a single call site so
each scanner does not have to thread line/column through itself - the
helper pulls them from the lexer state at the moment of emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_token with the supplied token_type/lexeme/literal_value
plus the current lexer.line and lexer.column. Appends the resulting
token pointer to lexer.tokens via ListCore.list_append.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_token" takes lexer_ptr as Integer, token_type as Integer, lexeme as String, literal_value as String:
    @Reasoning
    Create token and add to lexer's token list.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr

    Let token be proc create_token with token_type, lexeme, lexer.line, lexer.column, literal_value
    proc list_append from ListCore with lexer.tokens, token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records the first lex failure into the sticky had_error flag and
captures the diagnostic message. Subsequent calls overwrite the
message but had_error remains 1, ensuring callers see at least the
last error if multiple occur.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets had_error=1 on the lexer struct in place and copies message into
the error_message field.
@End Implementation
Process called "lexer_error" takes lexer_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    @Reasoning
    Record lexer error.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr

    Set lexer.had_error to 1
    Set lexer.error_message to message
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comments
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inter-token whitespace must be consumed between scans but newlines are
significant in Dockerfiles (they separate instructions), so this
routine deliberately only consumes the subset is_whitespace accepts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops while peek returns a whitespace character: each iteration calls
advance to consume the character. Exits as soon as peek returns a
non-whitespace codepoint (including newline or EOF).
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer_ptr as Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Skip spaces and tabs (but NOT newlines).
    @End Reasoning

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If proc is_whitespace with char is equal to 1:
            proc advance with lexer_ptr
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile comments start with `#` and run to end-of-line. The newline
itself is preserved (not consumed) so the line-counter logic in
advance still treats the line boundary as a significant statement
separator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peeks current character. Returns 0 if not 35 ('#'). Otherwise loops
advancing until peek returns 10 (newline) or 0 (EOF); both terminate
the loop without consuming. Returns 1 to signal "comment scanned".
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_comment" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan Dockerfile comment (# to end of line).
    Returns 1 if comment found, 0 otherwise.
    @End Reasoning

    Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

    If char is not equal to 35:  Note: '#'
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Skip comment until newline or EOF
    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If current is equal to 10:  Note: '\n'
            Set continue to 0
        End If

        If current is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Set continue to 0
        End If

        If continue is equal to 1:
            proc advance with lexer_ptr
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String and Identifier Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile strings support both single and double quotes. Common
escape sequences (\\n, \\t, \\\\, and the delimiter itself) are
recognized inside the body. The lexeme retains its quotes for
diagnostic display, while literal_value holds the decoded string the
parser will consume.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initializes string_value to "". Advances past the opening delimiter.
Loops until the matching delimiter or EOF: on EOF records "Unterminated
string" and returns 0. On the delimiter, advances past it and stops.
On 92 ('\\'), advances and dispatches on the escape character:
110='n'->10, 116='t'->9, 92='\\'->92, delimiter->delimiter; each case
appends the cooked codepoint to string_value via
StringPrimitive.string_concat + StringCore.char_to_string. For any other char calls
advance and appends the raw character. After the closing delimiter is
consumed, rebuilds the displayed lexeme by sandwiching string_value
between delim_str copies, then emits a TOKEN_STRING via add_token
with lexeme + literal_value. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_string" takes lexer_ptr as Integer, delimiter as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan quoted string with given delimiter (' or ").
    Handles escape sequences.
    @End Reasoning

    Let string_value be ""

    Note: Skip opening delimiter
    proc advance with lexer_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc is_at_end with lexer_ptr is equal to 1:
            proc lexer_error with lexer_ptr, "Unterminated string"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If char is equal to delimiter:
            Note: Found closing delimiter
            proc advance with lexer_ptr
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If char is equal to 92:  Note: '\' escape
                proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Let escape_char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

                If escape_char is equal to 110:  Note: 'n'
                    Set string_value to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with string_value, proc char_to_string from StringCore with 10
                    proc advance with lexer_ptr
                End If
                If escape_char is equal to 116:  Note: 't'
                    Set string_value to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with string_value, proc char_to_string from StringCore with 9
                    proc advance with lexer_ptr
                End If
                If escape_char is equal to 92:  Note: '\\'
                    Set string_value to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with string_value, proc char_to_string from StringCore with 92
                    proc advance with lexer_ptr
                End If
                If escape_char is equal to delimiter:
                    Set string_value to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with string_value, proc char_to_string from StringCore with delimiter
                    proc advance with lexer_ptr
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Let regular_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Set string_value to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with string_value, proc char_to_string from StringCore with regular_char
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Let delim_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with delimiter
    Let lexeme be proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with delim_str, string_value
    Set lexeme to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with lexeme, delim_str

    proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_STRING, lexeme, string_value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier scanning has two responsibilities: collect a run of
identifier characters, and classify the result as either a Dockerfile
instruction keyword (case-insensitive), one of the small reserved-word
keywords (AS, NONE), or a plain identifier. Doing the classification
here means the parser never has to second-guess token kinds.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures starting line/column for diagnostics. Loops calling advance
while peek returns an is_identifier_char codepoint, building the
identifier string via string_concat + char_to_string. Uppercases the
result via StringUtils.string_to_upper and feeds it to
get_instruction_type; on non-zero result emits a token of that
instruction kind. Otherwise checks for "AS" and "NONE" explicitly,
emitting TOKEN_AS / TOKEN_NONE; on no match emits TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. In
every case the original (non-uppercased) identifier is emitted as the
lexeme.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan identifier or keyword.
    @End Reasoning

    Let identifier be ""
    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Let start_line be lexer.line
    Let start_col be lexer.column

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If proc is_identifier_char with char is equal to 1:
            Let id_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
            Set identifier to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with identifier, proc char_to_string from StringCore with id_char
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check if it's a Dockerfile instruction (case-insensitive)
    Let upper_id be proc string_to_upper from StringUtils with identifier, 0
    Let token_type be proc get_instruction_type with upper_id

    If token_type is not equal to 0:
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, token_type, identifier, ""
    Otherwise:
        Note: Check for AS keyword
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "AS" is equal to 1:
            proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_AS, identifier, ""
        Otherwise:
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "NONE" is equal to 1:
                proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_NONE, identifier, ""
            Otherwise:
                Note: Regular identifier
                proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, identifier, ""
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps an uppercased identifier to its Dockerfile-instruction TOKEN_*
constant. Returning 0 for non-instructions lets the caller treat
non-zero as "this is an instruction keyword". A flat If chain over
canonical keywords is preferred to a hashtable lookup because the keyword
set is small and fixed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
String-equals comparison against each known instruction keyword
(FROM, RUN, CMD, LABEL, EXPOSE, ENV, ADD, COPY, ENTRYPOINT, VOLUME,
USER, WORKDIR, ARG, ONBUILD, STOPSIGNAL, HEALTHCHECK, SHELL, MAINTAINER,
etc.); returns the matching TOKEN_* constant on the first hit. Returns
0 if no keyword matches.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_instruction_type" takes instruction as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Map Dockerfile instruction to token type.
    @End Reasoning

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "FROM" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FROM
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "RUN" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_RUN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "CMD" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CMD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "LABEL" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LABEL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "EXPOSE" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_EXPOSE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "ENV" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ENV
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "ADD" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ADD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "COPY" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_COPY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "ENTRYPOINT" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ENTRYPOINT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "VOLUME" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_VOLUME
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "USER" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_USER
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "WORKDIR" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WORKDIR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "ARG" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ARG
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "ONBUILD" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ONBUILD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "STOPSIGNAL" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_STOPSIGNAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "HEALTHCHECK" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_HEALTHCHECK
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "SHELL" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SHELL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with instruction, "MAINTAINER" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_MAINTAINER
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not an instruction
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile variables come in two shapes: bare `$VAR` and braced
`${VAR}`. The braced form supports additional syntax (defaults,
patterns) downstream, so it must be preserved verbatim in the lexeme;
the bare form ends at the first non-identifier character.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initializes var_text to "$" and consumes the `$`. If next char is 123
('{'): appends `{`, advances, then accumulates a body of [A-Za-z0-9_]
chars; expects 125 ('}') closing - on success appends `}` and consumes
it, on mismatch records an error. For the bare form, accumulates the
same [A-Za-z0-9_] set without surrounding braces. Emits a TOKEN_VARIABLE
with the full var_text as lexeme. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_variable" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan variable substitution: $VAR or ${VAR}.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_text be "$"

    Note: Skip $
    proc advance with lexer_ptr

    Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

    Note: Check for ${VAR} syntax
    If char is equal to 123:  Note: '{'
        Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, "{"
        proc advance with lexer_ptr

        Note: Scan variable name
        Let continue be 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            Let current be proc peek with lexer_ptr

            If proc is_alpha with current is equal to 1:
                Let var_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
            Otherwise:
                If proc is_digit with current is equal to 1:
                    Set var_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                    Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
                Otherwise:
                    If current is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
                        Set var_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                        Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
                    Otherwise:
                        Set continue to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End While

        Note: Expect closing }
        Let closing be proc peek with lexer_ptr
        If closing is equal to 125:  Note: '}'
            Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, "}"
            proc advance with lexer_ptr
        Otherwise:
            proc lexer_error with lexer_ptr, "Expected '}' after variable name"
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: $VAR syntax - scan until non-identifier character
        Set continue to 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            Set current to proc peek with lexer_ptr

            If proc is_alpha with current is equal to 1:
                Set var_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
            Otherwise:
                If proc is_digit with current is equal to 1:
                    Set var_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                    Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
                Otherwise:
                    If current is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
                        Set var_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                        Set var_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with var_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with var_char
                    Otherwise:
                        Set continue to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_VARIABLE, var_text, ""
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dockerfile flags like `--from=stage` and `--chown=user:group` are
recognized as a single token so the parser does not have to assemble
the `--`-prefix from individual characters. The value part is included
in the lexeme so downstream consumers can split on `=` if needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initializes flag_text to "--" and consumes the two leading dashes.
Loops accumulating characters while peek is alpha, hyphen (45), equals
(61), or any is_identifier_char codepoint - matching the union of flag
name and value characters. Stops on any other character. Emits a
TOKEN_FLAG with the full flag_text as lexeme. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_flag" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan Dockerfile flags like --from=stage, --chown=user:group.
    @End Reasoning

    Let flag_text be "--"

    Note: Skip --
    proc advance with lexer_ptr
    proc advance with lexer_ptr

    Note: Scan flag name and value
    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
            Let flag_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
            Set flag_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with flag_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with flag_char
        Otherwise:
            If char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
                Set flag_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Set flag_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with flag_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with flag_char
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 61:  Note: '='
                    Set flag_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                    Set flag_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with flag_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with flag_char
                Otherwise:
                    If char is equal to 58:  Note: ':' as in --chown=user:group
                        Set flag_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                        Set flag_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with flag_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with flag_char
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc is_identifier_char with char is equal to 1:
                            Set flag_char to proc advance with lexer_ptr
                            Set flag_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with flag_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with flag_char
                        Otherwise:
                            Set continue to 0
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_FLAG, flag_text, ""
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The outer scanner dispatches on the first character of each token,
calling the appropriate sub-scanner. Skipping whitespace and comments
first means token dispatch never sees them, simplifying the dispatch
table. Newline is its own token because Dockerfiles are line-oriented.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls skip_whitespace. If scan_comment recognizes and consumes a
comment, returns 1. If at EOF, emits a TOKEN_EOF and returns 0. Peeks
the next character and dispatches: newline (10) -> consume and emit
TOKEN_NEWLINE; quote (34, 39) -> scan_string with the matching
delimiter; `$` (36) -> scan_variable; `--` (peek_ahead detects double
dash) -> scan_flag; alpha or underscore -> scan_identifier; digit ->
scan_identifier (Dockerfile identifiers can start with digits in some
contexts like image tags); any other recognized punctuation produces
its own single-character token. Unknown characters trigger
lexer_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_token" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Scan next token from source.
    Returns 1 if token scanned, 0 if at EOF or error.
    @End Reasoning

    proc skip_whitespace with lexer_ptr

    Note: Check for comments
    If proc scan_comment with lexer_ptr is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If proc is_at_end with lexer_ptr is equal to 1:
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_EOF, "", ""
        Return 0
    End If

    Let char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

    Note: Newline
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: '\n'
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_NEWLINE, "\\n", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Carriage return (skip)
    If char is equal to 13:  Note: '\r'
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Backslash (line continuation)
    If char is equal to 92:  Note: '\\'
        Let next_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer_ptr, 1

        If next_char is equal to 10:  Note: '\n'
            proc advance with lexer_ptr  Note: Skip \
            proc advance with lexer_ptr  Note: Skip \n
            proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_BACKSLASH, "\\", ""
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: JSON syntax
    If char is equal to 91:  Note: '['
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_LBRACKET, "[", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ']'
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_RBRACKET, "]", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ','
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_COMMA, ",", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Equals
    If char is equal to 61:  Note: '='
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_EQUALS, "=", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:  Note: ':' image-reference tag separator
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_COLON, ":", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 64:  Note: '@' image-reference digest separator
        proc advance with lexer_ptr
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_AT, "@", ""
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: String literals
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
        Return proc scan_string with lexer_ptr, 34
    End If

    If char is equal to 39:  Note: "'"
        Return proc scan_string with lexer_ptr, 39
    End If

    Note: Variable substitution
    If char is equal to 36:  Note: '$'
        Return proc scan_variable with lexer_ptr
    End If

    Note: Flags
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        Set next_char to proc peek_ahead with lexer_ptr, 1

        If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: '--'
            Return proc scan_flag with lexer_ptr
        End If
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier with lexer_ptr
    End If

    Note: Numbers and version-like tokens (EXPOSE ports like 8080, image tags
    Note: like 1.21 / 20.04 / 3.9-slim). A token that starts with a digit
    Note: continues across any identifier character (digits, '.', '-', letters,
    Note: '_', '/') so a dotted/hyphenated version lexes as one token rather
    Note: than fragmenting at the '.'.
    If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
        Let number be ""

        Let continue be 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            Let digit_char be proc peek with lexer_ptr

            If proc is_identifier_char with digit_char is equal to 1:
                Let digit be proc advance with lexer_ptr
                Set number to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with number, proc char_to_string from StringCore with digit
            Otherwise:
                Set continue to 0
            End If
        End While

        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_NUMBER, number, number
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Unquoted argument (everything else until whitespace/newline)
    Let arg_text be ""

    Set continue to 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc peek with lexer_ptr

        If current is equal to 10:  Note: '\n'
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                If proc is_whitespace with current is equal to 1:
                    Set continue to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Let arg_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
                    Set arg_text to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with arg_text, proc char_to_string from StringCore with arg_char
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If proc string_length from StringCore with arg_text is greater than 0:
        proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, arg_text, ""
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    Let unknown_char be proc advance with lexer_ptr
    Let error_msg be "Unexpected character: "
    Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, proc char_to_string from StringCore with unknown_char
    proc lexer_error with lexer_ptr, error_msg

    Let error_char_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with unknown_char
    proc add_token with lexer_ptr, TOKEN_ERROR, error_char_str, ""
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry point that drives scan_token to completion. Returns the
accumulated token list so the parser can consume it directly without
needing to know the internal lexer struct layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops calling scan_token; the loop exits when scan_token returns 0
(EOF or hard error). Reads the final lexer struct from memory and
returns its tokens List handle. The caller takes a borrowed reference -
ownership remains with the lexer until destruction.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tokenize entire source and return token list.
    @End Reasoning

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let result be proc scan_token with lexer_ptr

        If result is equal to 0:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return lexer_ptr.tokens
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the token list separate from tokenize so callers that
have already invoked tokenize can fetch the list later without
re-running the scanner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer struct and returns its tokens slot directly. Pure
read; no mutation.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_tokens" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Get list of tokens from lexer.
    @End Reasoning

    Return lexer_ptr.tokens
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean read of the sticky had_error flag for the parser/driver to
decide whether to proceed with the token stream or surface a lexical
error to the user.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer struct and returns its had_error field directly.
@End Implementation
Process called "had_error" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if lexer encountered errors.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Return lexer.had_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to had_error returning the last-set diagnostic. Callers are
expected to check had_error first; this routine returns an empty
string when no error has been set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer struct and returns its error_message field directly.
The string is borrowed from the lexer; the caller must not mutate or
free it.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_error_message" takes lexer_ptr as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Get error message if lexer encountered error.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer be lexer_ptr
    Return lexer.error_message
End Process
